  "Large infrastructure projects in Morocco involve diverse stakeholders: government ministries (tutelle), local authorities (commune, wali), funding agencies (international donors, banks), contractors, affected communities, media, and environmental groups. I would: 1) Stakeholder mapping — identify each stakeholder's interests, influence level, and preferred communication channels. 2) Communication plan — tailored messages for each group: technical reports for ministries, community impact briefings in Darija for local populations, progress reports for donors, and press releases for media. 3) Regular cadence — weekly progress reports to steering committee, monthly community updates, quarterly media briefings. 4) Community engagement — public consultations (enquête publique per Loi 12-03), information centers near construction sites, and grievance mechanisms. 5) Political sensitivity — coordinate messaging with government communications to ensure alignment. Morocco's social media activism means any community grievance can quickly become national news.",
