  "For a Moroccan business audience: 1) Language — present in French (business standard) with Arabic for emphasis or cultural touch. Slides in French, verbal examples in Darija if appropriate for informal settings. 2) Structure — begin with personal connection and context (relationship building), then present data and arguments, conclude with clear call to action. 3) Visual design — clean, professional slides with minimal text. Use Morocco-relevant images and data. Avoid cluttered slides — Moroccan executives appreciate elegance. 4) Cultural considerations — respect hierarchy by acknowledging senior attendees first, expect questions during the presentation (not just at the end), and be prepared for tangential discussions (this shows engagement, not distraction). 5) Data — Moroccan decision-makers value concrete numbers and ROI analysis. Reference local benchmarks and competitor examples. 6) Follow up — send a written summary (note de synthèse) after the presentation.",
